<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-147-266  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 266.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Feb 7 1990 n1494 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UK helicopter venture grounded by technology.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pancucci, Dom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A six-year effort to develop a multi-purpose helicopter which isalready nine months off target may slip even further while bidsare accepted for the mission control system.andP;  EH Industries, ajoint venture of Westland Helicopters of Yeovil, England andItalian firm Agusta, would normally expect to win the bid for thesystem due to its status as prime contractor.andP;  But the Ministry ofDefence has said the bidding process will be genuinely open,purportedly to guarantee that the control system is the bestavailable.andP;  Westland is expected to maintain its role as primecontractor whatever the results of the bid but may lose control ofthe systems and software side.andP;  In addition to the work slippage,there are doubts about the performance specification because SEMA,the software house commissioned by EHI to write the specificationhas yet to publish a detailed proposal after months of work.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Westland Helicopters Ltd. (contracts)Agusta S.p.A. (contracts).andO;Topic:     Defense ContractsGovernment ContractsEnglandSystem DesignControl SystemsAircraft.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>